 019:     """The famous *SVD* algorithm, as popularized by `Simon Funk
 020:     <http://sifter.org/~simon/journal/20061211.html>`_ during the Netflix
 021:     Prize. When baselines are not used, this is equivalent to Probabilistic
 022:     Matrix Factorization :cite:`salakhutdinov2008a` (see :ref:`note
 023:     <unbiased_note>` below).
 024: 
 025:     The prediction :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 026: 
 027:     .. math::
 028:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^Tp_u
 029: 
 030:     If user :math:`u` is unknown, then the bias :math:`b_u` and the factors
 031:     :math:`p_u` are assumed to be zero. The same applies for item :math:`i`
 032:     with :math:`b_i` and :math:`q_i`.
 033: 
 034:     For details, see equation (5) from :cite:`Koren:2009`. See also
 035:     :cite:`Ricci:2010`, section 5.3.1.
 036: 
 037:     To estimate all the unknown, we minimize the following regularized squared
 038:     error:
 039: 
 040:     .. math::
 041:         \sum_{r_{ui} \in R_{train}} \left(r_{ui} - \hat{r}_{ui} \\right)^2 +
 042:         \lambda\\left(b_i^2 + b_u^2 + ||q_i||^2 + ||p_u||^2\\right)
 043: 
 044: 
 045:     The minimization is performed by a very straightforward stochastic gradient
 046:     descent:
 047: 
 048:     .. math::
 049:         b_u &\\leftarrow b_u &+ \gamma (e_{ui} - \lambda b_u)\\\\
 050:         b_i &\\leftarrow b_i &+ \gamma (e_{ui} - \lambda b_i)\\\\
 051:         p_u &\\leftarrow p_u &+ \gamma (e_{ui} \\cdot q_i - \lambda p_u)\\\\
 052:         q_i &\\leftarrow q_i &+ \gamma (e_{ui} \\cdot p_u - \lambda q_i)
 053: 
 054:     where :math:`e_{ui} = r_{ui} - \\hat{r}_{ui}`. These steps are performed
 055:     over all the ratings of the trainset and repeated ``n_epochs`` times.
 056:     Baselines are initialized to ``0``. User and item factors are randomly
 057:     initialized according to a normal distribution, which can be tuned using
 058:     the ``init_mean`` and ``init_std_dev`` parameters.
 059: 
 060:     You also have control over the learning rate :math:`\gamma` and the
 061:     regularization term :math:`\lambda`. Both can be different for each
 062:     kind of parameter (see below). By default, learning rates are set to
 063:     ``0.005`` and regularization terms are set to ``0.02``.
 064: 
 065:     .. _unbiased_note:
 066: 
 067:     .. note::
 068:         You can choose to use an unbiased version of this algorithm, simply
 069:         predicting:
 070: 
 071:         .. math::
 072:             \hat{r}_{ui} = q_i^Tp_u
 073: 
 074:         This is equivalent to Probabilistic Matrix Factorization
 075:         (:cite:`salakhutdinov2008a`, section 2) and can be achieved by setting
 076:         the ``biased`` parameter to ``False``.
 077: 
 078: 
 079:     Args:
 080:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``100``.
 081:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 082:             ``20``.
 083:         biased(bool): Whether to use baselines (or biases). See :ref:`note
 084:             <unbiased_note>` above.  Default is ``True``.
 085:         init_mean: The mean of the normal distribution for factor vectors
 086:             initialization. Default is ``0``.
 087:         init_std_dev: The standard deviation of the normal distribution for
 088:             factor vectors initialization. Default is ``0.1``.
 089:         lr_all: The learning rate for all parameters. Default is ``0.005``.
 090:         reg_all: The regularization term for all parameters. Default is
 091:             ``0.02``.
 092:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence over
 093:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 094:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence over
 095:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 096:         lr_pu: The learning rate for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence over
 097:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 098:         lr_qi: The learning rate for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence over
 099:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 100:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence
 101:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 102:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence
 103:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 104:         reg_pu: The regularization term for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence
 105:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 106:         reg_qi: The regularization term for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence
 107:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 108:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 109:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 110:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 111:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 112:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 113:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 114:             ``None``.
 115:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 116:

 165:         # however, Funk seems to implicitly say that the algo looks like this
 166:         # (see reg below):
 167:         # for f in range(n_factors):
 168:         #       for _ in range(n_iter):
 169:         #           for u, i, r in all_ratings:
 170:         #               err = r_ui - <p[u, :f+1], q[i, :f+1]>
 171:         #               update p[u, f]
 172:         #               update q[i, f]
 173:         # which is also the way https://github.com/aaw/IncrementalSVD.jl
 174:         # implemented it.
 175:         #
 176:         # Funk: "Anyway, this will train one feature (aspect), and in
 177:         # particular will find the most prominent feature remaining (the one
 178:         # that will most reduce the error that's left over after previously
 179:         # trained features have done their best). When it's as good as it's
 180:         # going to get, shift it onto the pile of done features, and start a
 181:         # new one. For efficiency's sake, cache the residuals (all 100 million
 182:         # of them) so when you're training feature 72 you don't have to wait
 183:         # for predictRating() to re-compute the contributions of the previous
 184:         # 71 features. You will need 2 Gig of ram, a C compiler, and good
 185:         # programming habits to do this."

 284:     """The *SVD++* algorithm, an extension of :class:`SVD` taking into account
 285:     implicit ratings.
 286: 
 287:     The prediction :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 288: 
 289:     .. math::
 290:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^T\\left(p_u +
 291:         |I_u|^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \sum_{j \\in I_u}y_j\\right)
 292: 
 293:     Where the :math:`y_j` terms are a new set of item factors that capture
 294:     implicit ratings. Here, an implicit rating describes the fact that a user
 295:     :math:`u` rated an item :math:`j`, regardless of the rating value.
 296: 
 297:     If user :math:`u` is unknown, then the bias :math:`b_u` and the factors
 298:     :math:`p_u` are assumed to be zero. The same applies for item :math:`i`
 299:     with :math:`b_i`, :math:`q_i` and :math:`y_i`.
 300: 
 301: 
 302:     For details, see section 4 of :cite:`Koren:2008:FMN`. See also
 303:     :cite:`Ricci:2010`, section 5.3.1.
 304: 
 305:     Just as for :class:`SVD`, the parameters are learned using a SGD on the
 306:     regularized squared error objective.
 307: 
 308:     Baselines are initialized to ``0``. User and item factors are randomly
 309:     initialized according to a normal distribution, which can be tuned using
 310:     the ``init_mean`` and ``init_std_dev`` parameters.
 311: 
 312:     You have control over the learning rate :math:`\gamma` and the
 313:     regularization term :math:`\lambda`. Both can be different for each
 314:     kind of parameter (see below). By default, learning rates are set to
 315:     ``0.005`` and regularization terms are set to ``0.02``.
 316: 
 317:     Args:
 318:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``20``.
 319:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 320:             ``20``.
 321:         init_mean: The mean of the normal distribution for factor vectors
 322:             initialization. Default is ``0``.
 323:         init_std_dev: The standard deviation of the normal distribution for
 324:             factor vectors initialization. Default is ``0.1``.
 325:         lr_all: The learning rate for all parameters. Default is ``0.007``.
 326:         reg_all: The regularization term for all parameters. Default is
 327:             ``0.02``.
 328:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence over
 329:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 330:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence over
 331:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 332:         lr_pu: The learning rate for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence over
 333:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 334:         lr_qi: The learning rate for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence over
 335:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 336:         lr_yj: The learning rate for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence over
 337:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 338:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence
 339:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 340:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence
 341:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 342:         reg_pu: The regularization term for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence
 343:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 344:         reg_qi: The regularization term for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence
 345:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 346:         reg_yj: The regularization term for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence
 347:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 348:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 349:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 350:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 351:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 352:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 353:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 354:             ``None``.
 355:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 356: 
 357:     Attributes:
 358:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 359:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 360:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 361:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)

 363:             factors (only exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 364:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 365:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 366:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only

 542:     """A collaborative filtering algorithm based on Non-negative Matrix
 543:     Factorization.
 544: 
 545:     This algorithm is very similar to :class:`SVD`. The prediction
 546:     :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 547: 
 548:     .. math::
 549:         \hat{r}_{ui} = q_i^Tp_u,
 550: 
 551:     where user and item factors are kept **positive**. Our implementation
 552:     follows that suggested in :cite:`NMF:2014`, which is equivalent to
 553:     :cite:`Zhang96` in its non-regularized form. Both are direct applications
 554:     of NMF for dense matrices :cite:`NMF_algo`.
 555: 
 556:     The optimization procedure is a (regularized) stochastic gradient descent
 557:     with a specific choice of step size that ensures non-negativity of factors,
 558:     provided that their initial values are also positive.
 559: 
 560:     At each step of the SGD procedure, the factors :math:`f` or user :math:`u`
 561:     and item :math:`i` are updated as follows:
 562: 
 563:     .. math::
 564:         p_{uf} &\\leftarrow p_{uf} &\cdot \\frac{\\sum_{i \in I_u} q_{if}
 565:         \\cdot r_{ui}}{\\sum_{i \in I_u} q_{if} \\cdot \\hat{r_{ui}} +
 566:         \\lambda_u |I_u| p_{uf}}\\\\
 567:         q_{if} &\\leftarrow q_{if} &\cdot \\frac{\\sum_{u \in U_i} p_{uf}
 568:         \\cdot r_{ui}}{\\sum_{u \in U_i} p_{uf} \\cdot \\hat{r_{ui}} +
 569:         \lambda_i |U_i| q_{if}}\\\\
 570: 
 571:     where :math:`\lambda_u` and :math:`\lambda_i` are regularization
 572:     parameters.
 573: 
 574:     This algorithm is highly dependent on initial values. User and item factors
 575:     are uniformly initialized between ``init_low`` and ``init_high``. Change
 576:     them at your own risks!
 577: 
 578:     A biased version is available by setting the ``biased`` parameter to
 579:     ``True``. In this case, the prediction is set as
 580: 
 581:     .. math::
 582:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^Tp_u,
 583: 
 584:     still ensuring positive factors. Baselines are optimized in the same way as
 585:     in the :class:`SVD` algorithm. While yielding better accuracy, the biased
 586:     version seems highly prone to overfitting so you may want to reduce the
 587:     number of factors (or increase regularization).
 588: 
 589:     Args:
 590:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``15``.
 591:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 592:             ``50``.
 593:         biased(bool): Whether to use baselines (or biases). Default is
 594:             ``False``.
 595:         reg_pu: The regularization term for users :math:`\lambda_u`. Default is
 596:             ``0.06``.
 597:         reg_qi: The regularization term for items :math:`\lambda_i`. Default is
 598:             ``0.06``.
 599:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Only relevant for
 600:             biased version. Default is ``0.02``.
 601:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Only relevant for
 602:             biased version. Default is ``0.02``.
 603:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Only relevant for biased
 604:             version. Default is ``0.005``.
 605:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Only relevant for biased
 606:             version. Default is ``0.005``.
 607:         init_low: Lower bound for random initialization of factors. Must be
 608:             greater than ``0`` to ensure non-negative factors. Default is
 609:             ``0``.
 610:         init_high: Higher bound for random initialization of factors. Default
 611:             is ``1``.
 612:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 613:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 614:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 615:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 616:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 617:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 618:             ``None``.
 619:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 620: 
 621:     Attributes:
 622:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 623:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 624:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 625:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 626:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
